Run this little program and you&#39;ll understand that removing items without adjusting the index means that you skip items:
```java
class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {

        List&lt;String&gt; l = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(&quot;A&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;C&quot;, &quot;D&quot;));

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; l.size(); ++i) {
            System.out.println(&quot;Checking &quot; + l.get(i));
            if (&quot;B&quot;.equals(l.get(i))) {
                l.remove(i);
            }
        }

    }
}
```

You need to decrement `i` after removing an item, i.e. 
```
...
            if (&quot;B&quot;.equals(l.get(i))) {
                l.remove(i);
                i--;
            }
...
```

Alternatively, use an `Iterator`, as Old Dog suggested:
```
class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {

        List&lt;String&gt; l = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(&quot;A&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;C&quot;, &quot;D&quot;));
        Iterator&lt;String&gt; i = l.iterator();
        while (i.hasNext()) {
            String s = i.next();
            System.out.println(&quot;Checking &quot; + s);
            if (&quot;B&quot;.equals(s)) {
                i.remove();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

